# ADR-0011: FastAPI + Postgres + B2 (self-hosted backend)

## Context

adr-0002-backend-self-host-strategy planned **self-hosted Supabase via Docker**. The repo now ships a **slimmer stack**: own API, own auth, external object storage — better fit for CPX22 RAM and solo ops (optional **Coolify** for deploy UI).

## Decision

**Production target (Layer B backend):**

| Concern | Choice |
|---------|--------|
| API | FastAPI + Uvicorn (`backend/app/`) |
| Database | PostgreSQL + PostGIS |
| Auth | Argon2id + JWT/refresh (not Supabase Auth on cutover) |
| Images | Backblaze B2 presigned uploads (`/uploads/presign`) |
| Deploy | Docker Compose on Hetzner; **Coolify** optional (proxy replaces Caddy in compose) |

**Flutter:** Repository pattern (adr-0008-data-access-repository-pattern-for-portability) with `ApiClient` when `USE_LEGACY_SUPABASE=false`. Default remains legacy Supabase until cutover.

**Password migration:** Supabase password hashes are **not portable** — users reset passwords per cutover runbook (repo: `docs/DEPLOY.md` (auth cutover section)).

## Consequences

**Positive:** Lower RAM than full Supabase stack; clear ownership of auth and schema; B2 avoids VPS disk for photos.

**Negative:** No Supabase Realtime/RLS out of the box — chat/realtime needs a later ADR; more custom backend work.

**Neutral:** adr-0007-auth-strategy-supabase-otp-plus-apple-google may need revision when Apple/Google login moves to FastAPI.

